Step 3 : Visualising the data¶

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(16,9))
plt.title("Heatmap")
sns.heatmap(data=df.corr(),annot=True)
Out[ ]:
<AxesSubplot:title={'center':'Heatmap'}>

It is inferred that the number of drivers per billion miles are highly correlated with cases pertaining to percentage of drivers either impaired with alcohol(0.85), or having no previous cases of fatal accidents(0.96).

It is also inferred that most cases which involved people with no previous fatal accidents, were under the influence of alcohol, with a correlation of both of those factors coming out at 0.78.

Therefore, It can be said that most cases happened with people who were under the influence of alcohol and previously had no fatal accidents.

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(25,14))
top_state = df.loc[df['total'].idxmax()]
sns.barplot(x="abbrev", y="total", data=df, palette="viridis")
for index, row in df.iterrows():
    if row["abbrev"] == top_state["abbrev"]:
        plt.annotate(f'{row["abbrev"]}\n{row["total"]}',
                    xy=(index, row["total"]),
                    xytext=(0, 10), 
                    textcoords='offset points',
                    ha='center',
                    fontsize=12,
                    color='red',  
                    bbox=dict(boxstyle='round,pad=0.3', edgecolor='gray', facecolor='lightyellow'))
    else:
        plt.annotate(f'{row["abbrev"]}\n{row["total"]}',
                    xy=(index, row["total"]),
                    xytext=(0, 10), 
                    textcoords='offset points',
                    ha='center',
                    fontsize=12,
                    color='black',  
                    bbox=dict(boxstyle='round,pad=0.3', edgecolor='gray', facecolor='lightyellow'))
plt.xlabel("State Abbreviation")
plt.ylabel("Total Fatal Accidents")
plt.title("Total Fatal Accidents by State")
Out[ ]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Total Fatal Accidents by State')

As we see in this barchart, the states of North Dakota and South Carolina, have the highest fatal accidents, with 23.9 accidents per billion miles
